    "title": "Neshek — \"Usury\" or \"Biting Interest\"",
    "description": "The Hebrew word neshek, from the root meaning \"to bite,\" carries the image of something devouring flesh. To charge interest to a brother is to let debt bite into his very substance. The Law of Moses explicitly forbade lending at interest to fellow Israelites (Exodus 22:25; Leviticus 25:35–37). To exact neshek is not merely bad business — it is to devour your brother.",
